hire, England","England":"England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"en":{"1102–1151":"1102–1151","1105–Male":"1105–Deceased","1106–Female":"1106–Deceased","1107–1157":"1107–1157","1102–Female":"1102–Deceased","1126–1196":"1126–1196","1130–Male":"1130–Deceased","1083–1106":"1083–1106","1082–1105":"1082–1105","1107":"1107","1106":"1106","1105":"1105","1126":"1126","1102":"1102","1157":"1157","1130":"1130","1196":"1196","1151":"1151","8 January 1106":"8 January 1106","1083":"1083","1082":"1082","Corbins Hall, Staffordshire, England":"Corbins Hall, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English: nickname meaning ‘little crow, raven’, possibly applied to a black haired man, from Old French, Middle English <i>corbin</i>, a diminutive of <i>corb</i> ‘raven’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>corbin</i>, <i>corfbin</i> ‘crow, raven’).","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the places in Calvados and Orne, France, named Corbon.","Irish: variant of   Corban  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carbin","meanings":["Swedish: soldier's name, from Swedish <i>karbin</i> ‘carbine’, a type of short rifle or musket used by cavalry.","Cornish: hypercorrect backformation from Cornish <i>carr-bons</i> ‘causeway’, or a habitational name from Carbis in Lelant (Cornwall), of the same derivation.","English: variant of   Corbin  ."]},{"name":"Corvin","meanings":["English (Durham): possibly a variant of   Corbin  .","Altered form of Scottish, Irish or English   Colvin  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Korving</b> (mainly The Hague): from the personal name <i>Korving</i>, from <i>Corvinus</i>, from Latin <i>corvus</i> ‘raven’."]},{"name":"Corban","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Corbáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Corbán</i>’ or <b>Ó Coirbín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Coirbín</i>’, both possibly from an occupational name based on <i>corb</i> ‘chariot’. Both names have also been Anglicized as   Corbett  .","Irish: alternatively, a variant of <b>Currivan</b>, from <b>Ó Coirbheáin</b>, itself a variant of   Corban   (pronounced with three syllables in Irish).","Romanian: nickname derived from <i>corb</i> ‘crow’, with the augmentative suffix <i>-an</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705185,"age":4,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Corbin III was born in 1102, in England, his father, Robert Corbin II, was 19 and his mother, Baroness Abelone de Corbyn, was 20. He died in 1151, in Staffordshire, England, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1102–1151":"1102–1151","1105–Male":"1105–Sur